		<header class="entry-header">

			<h1 class="entry-title">Cheap Fridge Outlets</h1>

		</header>

		<div class="entry-content">

			<p>Cheap fridges can be picked up online from many large reputable UK retailers. Typically you can save about 30% on refurbished and damaged fridges but often you can save even more. Everything you need to know about where to buy, and how to get the most efficient and hygienic fridge for less is below.</p>
<hr />
<h1><span style="color: #333399;">Freezers 4 star rating explained</span></h1>
<p><img class="alignleft" title="Samsung Fridge" src="http://farm7.staticflickr.com/6107/6347612223_b7f2d86518.jpg" alt="Samsung Fridge" width="326" /><br />
<span style="color: #333333;">Not all freezers where created equal. Check the standard 4 star rating used across Europe to grade freezers. Freezers are rated from 1 star to 4 depending on how they perform. 4 stars being the highest rating. Fresh food (dependant on type, i.e. meat, vegetables, fruit etc) will stay fresh in a freezer for 3-12 months if is kept below -18 °C. Only fridges with a three star rating and above will offer this temperature. It is a common misconception that food is safe if it is frozen but many bacteria that cause food to decay can live at temperature below the freezing point (0°C).  </span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="color: #333333;"><strong>Use the definitions below to work out what you need. </strong></span></p>
<h2><span style="text-decoration: underline; color: #e71762;">Stars</span></h2>
<ul>
<div style="float:right; margin: 15px;">
<p><script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "ca-pub-5658586300241391";
/* small rect cheap fridge */
google_ad_slot = "0850517961";
google_ad_width = 300;
google_ad_height = 250;
//-->
</script><br />
<script type="text/javascript"
src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script></p>
</div>
<li><span style="color: #333333;"><strong>1 star </strong>The minimum operating temperature is -6 °C. Pre-frozen food can be stored for up to one week.</span></li>
<li><span style="color: #333333;"><strong>2 star</strong> Will Operate at -12 °C allowing pre-frozen food to be store for one month.</span></li>
<li><span style="color: #333333;"><strong>3 star</strong> Operating temperature is -18 °C or below. Pre frozen food can be stored up to 12 months depending on type.</span></li>
<li><span style="color: #333333;"><strong>4 star</strong> These are the only fridges designed to freeze fresh (none-frozen) foods. Although they run at the same recommended -18 °C as the 3 star fridges they will have a fast freeze function which can lower the freezer down to -26 °C if it needs to. This is useful when you are introducing new foods at room temperature to the freezer.  With out a fast freeze setting the new food could raise the temperature of the freezer and negatively effecting freshness of the food that is already frozen.</span></li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h1><span style="color: #333399;">European Union Energy Label (refrigeration) </span><span style="color: #333399;">Explained</span></h1>
<p><span style="color: #333333;"> In Europe fridges and freezer are all rated for energy efficiency using  one system. It is important to get the most energy efficient fridge that you can not only to help minimise our impact on the environment but also to save you money. People often forget that a fridge is probably the only thing in your house you will never turn off and generally people only buy  new ones when they brake or become obsolete.</span></p>
<blockquote><p><span style="color: #e71762;">The rating is worked out from the amount of energy used per set volume. So remember that a bigger fridge may still use more power even if it&#8217;s rating is higher. Fridges and freezers are rated from A+++ (the most efficient) to G (the least efficient)</span></p></blockquote>
<p><span style="color: #333333;">The Numbers are some what meaningless  unless your are a scientist or mathematical but what we can see is that the most efficient fridges use at least 6 times less energy than the worst rated.  Now that&#8217;s food for thought.</span></p>
<p><span style="color: #333333;">Energy Efficiently Index results for each rating: A<sup>+++</sup>&lt;22  A<sup>++</sup>&lt;30 A<sup>+</sup>&lt;42/44  A&lt;55  B&lt;75  C&lt;95  D&lt;110  E&lt;125  F&lt;15o  G&gt;150</span></p>
<p>To read more about energy efficiently check out the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Union_energy_label">Wikipedia page</a>.</p>
<hr />
<h1><span style="color: #333399;">Top 3 cheap fridge outlets.</span></h1>
